
# Template Method Pattern (Refined Notes)

## Intent
- Define the skeleton of an algorithm in a base class
- Defer specific steps to subclasses
- Allow subclasses to redefine parts without changing overall structure
- Pipeline the methods for a bigger task in a fixed order of subtasks 

## Structure
- AbstractClass
  - templateMethod() → defines algorithm structure  
  - primitiveOperations() → abstract steps implemented by subclasses  
  - hooks() → optional override points  
- ConcreteClass
  - implements specific steps of the algorithm  

## When to Use
- Multiple classes share the same algorithm structure but differ in steps  
- Want to enforce a fixed sequence of operations  
- Need to avoid code duplication across similar workflows  
- Want controlled extension points in an algorithm  

## Core Idea
- Base class defines **"what to do and in what order"**  
- Subclasses define **"how each step is done"**  

## What It Solves
- Eliminates duplicated algorithm structure  
- Prevents inconsistent implementations of workflows  
- Centralizes control over execution flow  

## What You Already Have (Sharpened)
- Inheritance-based reuse of behavior  
- Fixed workflow with customizable steps  
- Control inversion:
  - base class drives execution  
  - subclasses fill in details  

## Preconditions
- There exists a common algorithm structure  
- Variations can be isolated into individual steps  
- Subclasses are allowed to extend behavior without breaking flow  

## Postconditions
- Algorithm structure is consistent across implementations  
- Subclasses customize only specific steps  
- Changes to workflow happen in one place (base class)  

## Trade-offs

### Pros
- Promotes code reuse (common logic in base class)  
- Enforces consistent algorithm structure  
- Reduces duplication across subclasses  
- Provides clear extension points (hooks)  

### Cons
- Relies on inheritance (less flexible than composition)  
- Changes in base class can impact all subclasses  
- Can lead to rigid designs if overused  
- Harder to understand due to control inversion  

## Subtle but Important Insight
- Shifts from:
  - "each class defines its own algorithm"  
  - to "base class defines the algorithm, subclasses customize steps"  

This enables:
- controlled extensibility  
- consistency across implementations  
- reuse of invariant logic  

## Variants
- Hook Method Pattern → optional steps overridden selectively  
- Hollywood Principle → "Don't call us, we'll call you"  
- Template + Factory Method → defer object creation to subclasses  

## Comparisons
- vs Strategy → composition + runtime selection vs inheritance + fixed structure  
- vs Factory Method → focuses on object creation vs full algorithm structure  
- vs Command → encapsulates actions vs defines execution flow  